		<exercise xml:id="rose-gold-using-equations">
			<introduction>
				<p>
					<q>Rose gold</q> is a mix of gold and copper. We start with 2 grams of an alloy that is equal parts gold and copper and add <m>A</m> grams of pure gold to lighten the color. The percentage of gold in the resulting rose gold alloy, <m>R</m> is given by <me>R = 100\left(\frac{1+A}{2+A}\right)</me> For example, if we add 0.8 grams of pure gold, then <m>A=0.8</m> and so the percentage is <me>R=100\left(\frac{1+0.8}{2+0.8}\right)= 100 \times (1 + \underline{0.8})\div(2+\underline{0.8})=64.28571428\ldots \approx 64.3\%</me>
					<em>
						(Story also appears in
						<xref ref="rose-gold-order-operations" />, 
						<xref ref="rose-gold-algebraic-notation" />, 
						and 4.1 Exercises)
					</em>
				</p>
			</introduction>
